Read the transformation matrix using 

    var el = document.getElementById(&quot;element2&quot;);
    var st = window.getComputedStyle(el, null);
    var tr = st.getPropertyValue(&quot;transform&quot;);

`tr` should be a string that looks like this (assuming 2D transform type)

    matrix(0.8660254037844387, 0.49999999999999994, -0.49999999999999994, 0.8660254037844387, 0, 0)

then extract those 6 values which might take a bit of parsing (see link below). Multiply each element by -1 or do whatever the appropriate inverse operation is and set the new transform with

    document.getElementById(&quot;element1&quot;).style.transform = matrix(a, b, c, d, e, f)

Source: https://css-tricks.com/get-value-of-css-rotation-through-javascript/

However, if you&#39;ve defined the transform of `element2` yourself, then it would be much easier to just invert the input to that and define it for `element1` in the same way rather than trying to recover it from `element2`.

